{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"73e1ef35-9312-4ab8-9ba2-f276e14f4a9a","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For a quicker look, `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` shows live CPU/GC metrics before committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a7a35059-51eb-4e28-a595-6891176b134b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to collect a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're seeing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"9420:1422E9:1F7C02A:23649C0:69E81D16"},"id":"b500a94e-22d3-4a0c-a4fc-caf5e801a91d","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:58:07.898Z","parentId":"e2f4ed68-f581-4e73-8bc0-acc0b5f9da31"}
